*   We need \ce{6NaF} on the reactant side. We can get this by reversing Reaction 3 and multiplying it by 6:
    6 * (\ce{NaOH + HF -> H2O + NaF})  becomes \ce{6NaOH + 6HF -> 6H2O + 6NaF}.  ΔH'₃ = 6 * (-61.5) = \pu{-369 kJ mol^{-1}}
*   We need \ce{6HCl} on the reactant side. We can get this by multiplying Reaction 1 by 6:
    6 * (\ce{NaOH + HCl -> NaCl + H2O}) becomes \ce{6NaOH + 6HCl -> 6NaCl + 6H2O}. ΔH'₁ = 6 * (-56.7) = \pu{-340.2 kJ mol^{-1}}

